content.description: Stiff start leads up to nice features and a good shake. Then up to the easy-looking, but not-quite-easy pillar up high. Something to think about all the way. Pillar feature is very cool.3rd bolt needs a cabledraw maybe.
content.location: A striking rib/pillar that starts at about 2/3 height. Just right of Disco's orange streak.Start is just about the lowest point of crag.

content.description: Steady pulling on cool holds. Slightly overhanging. Go RIGHT following the orange streak at the bakerized 4th bolt. Going left into the grungy black crack is not as fun and may make it very hard to clip the 5th bolt.Sequence is not obvious at the top and the meter is running.2.5 stars from me. Rounding up to 3 in this case.
content.location: Main face (first stone encountered on approach) has 2 obvious orange streaks. This route is the left streak. Starts atop the boulder just left of lowest point of crag.

content.description: A stiffish start past 2 bolts gives way to a super-fun 5.9ish finish up nice features on a slight overhang. Even the easy parts keep you thinking.Josie indicated that it might really be 5.11- especially for her height.I use the term "disco fever" to describe the tendency of newbie FAists to overstar their own FAs.
content.location: The right side orange streak with cool pillar formation at mid-height. Starts near lowest point of crag.

content.description: Little crag near Summerhaven. Pretty hang, morning shade.Many upper sabino crags have names from the military alphabet. Alpha Bravo Charlie Delta Echo Foxtrot. Alpha might be awesome but has no routes due to a long approach. Bravo is probably too small. Charlie (and Lony Tusk) are never visited. Delta Echo Foxtrot are easier to get to.
